As Igor noted, the best explanations are in the user manual and the &#39;?&#39; 
help text that can be called up from the web user interface.

I have interspersed some other comments about your rules below:


&gt;  &lt;newObject name=&quot;decide-rules&quot; class=&quot;org.archive.crawler.deciderules.DecideRuleSequence&quot;&gt;
&gt; &#8722;
&gt;  &lt;map name=&quot;rules&quot;&gt;
&gt; &#8722;
&gt;  &lt;newObject name=&quot;Surt Rule&quot; class=&quot;org.archive.crawler.deciderules.SurtPrefixedDecideRule&quot;&gt;
&gt; &lt;string name=&quot;decision&quot;&gt;ACCEPT&lt;/string&gt;
&gt; &lt;string name=&quot;surts-source-file&quot;/&gt;
&gt; &lt;boolean name=&quot;seeds-as-surt-prefixes&quot;&gt;true&lt;/boolean&gt;
&gt; &lt;string name=&quot;surts-dump-file&quot;&gt;dump.txt&lt;/string&gt;
&gt; &lt;boolean name=&quot;also-check-via&quot;&gt;false&lt;/boolean&gt;
&gt; &lt;boolean name=&quot;rebuild-on-reconfig&quot;&gt;true&lt;/boolean&gt;
&gt; &lt;/newObject&gt;
&gt; &#8722;
&gt;  &lt;newObject name=&quot;Trans Rule&quot; class=&quot;org.archive.crawler.deciderules.TransclusionDecideRule&quot;&gt;
&gt; &lt;integer name=&quot;max-trans-hops&quot;&gt;5&lt;/integer&gt;
&gt; &lt;integer name=&quot;max-speculative-hops&quot;&gt;1&lt;/integer&gt;
&gt; &lt;/newObject&gt;

&#39;5&#39; is a very high number of hops to transclude. It means up to 5 &#39;E&#39; or 
&#39;R&#39; hops will be included, regardless of whether they are on your 
starting sites.

&gt; &#8722;
&gt;  &lt;newObject name=&quot;Scope One Rule&quot; class=&quot;org.archive.crawler.deciderules.ScopePlusOneDecideRule&quot;&gt;
&gt; &lt;string name=&quot;decision&quot;&gt;ACCEPT&lt;/string&gt;
&gt; &lt;string name=&quot;surts-source-file&quot;/&gt;
&gt; &lt;boolean name=&quot;seeds-as-surt-prefixes&quot;&gt;false&lt;/boolean&gt;
&gt; &lt;string name=&quot;surts-dump-file&quot;&gt;&lt;/string&gt;
&gt; &lt;boolean name=&quot;also-check-via&quot;&gt;false&lt;/boolean&gt;
&gt; &lt;boolean name=&quot;rebuild-on-reconfig&quot;&gt;true&lt;/boolean&gt;
&gt; &lt;string name=&quot;host-or-domain-scope&quot;&gt;Host&lt;/string&gt;
&gt; &lt;/newObject&gt;

This rule is not configured to take its allowable SURT prefixes from 
seeds, or from a file. So it essentially has no effect.

If you do want a &#39;one hop off&#39; allowance, it is better achieved with the 
&#39;also-check-via&#39; setting on your topmost SURT rule, which is more simple 
way to do the same thing as the ScopePlusOneDecideRule.

&gt; &#8722;
&gt;  &lt;newObject name=&quot;Hopes Path Rule&quot; class=&quot;org.archive.crawler.deciderules.HopsPathMatchesRegExpDecideRule&quot;&gt;
&gt; &lt;string name=&quot;decision&quot;&gt;REJECT&lt;/string&gt;
&gt; &lt;string name=&quot;regexp&quot;&gt;.*E$&lt;/string&gt;
&gt; &lt;/newObject&gt;

This will reject everything discovered via an &#39;E&#39; hop, even if on your 
starting sites.

&gt; &#8722;
&gt;  &lt;newObject name=&quot;Too Hops Rule&quot; class=&quot;org.archive.crawler.deciderules.TooManyHopsDecideRule&quot;&gt;
&gt; &lt;integer name=&quot;max-hops&quot;&gt;20&lt;/integer&gt;
&gt; &lt;/newObject&gt;
&gt; &#8722;
&gt;  &lt;newObject name=&quot;Content Type Rule&quot; class=&quot;org.archive.crawler.deciderules.ContentTypeMatchesRegExpDecideRule&quot;&gt;
&gt; &lt;string name=&quot;decision&quot;&gt;ACCEPT&lt;/string&gt;
&gt; &lt;string name=&quot;regexp&quot;&gt;(?i)text/html.*&lt;/string&gt;
&gt; &lt;/newObject&gt;

Since scoping is performed when only the URI is available -- it has not 
yet been fetched, so its content-type is not known -- the 
ContentTypeMatchesRegExpDecideRule is not useful in a scope. (It was 
designed for use elsewhere.)

